    "Article 14 of the Indian Constitution guarantees equality before the law and equal protection of the laws within the territory of India. This fundamental right prohibits discrimination on grounds of religion, race, caste, sex, or place of birth. It ensures that all persons are treated equally by the State and that no person shall be denied equality before the law or equal protection of the laws. This article forms the foundation of the rule of law in India and ensures that the State cannot deny to any person equality before the law or the equal protection of the laws. The principle of equality is a basic feature of the Constitution and cannot be taken away even by constitutional amendment."
